issue.title: [Bug]: Numeric values in postgres can be too long for BigQuery numeric datatype
issue.body:
### Related Template(s)

Datastream-to-Bigquery

### What happened?

I have used Datastream to BigQuery template, where Postgres is source of the Datastream.

Most of it works fine so far except som numeric values, which are too long for BigQuery's numeric datatype
![image](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/DataflowTemplates/assets/146851374/461cccba-0c32-4d0f-8104-ee73090e7c23)

In postgres it is numeric value as this - 55.066315446079813 will fail when Dataflow tries to put into BigQuery. The error lands in deadletterqueue and never resovels.

{"debugInfo":"","location":"latitude_wsg84","message":"Invalid NUMERIC value: 55.066315446079813","reason":"invalid"}],"index":0}

If I manually insert the value i BigQuery it will not fail as Dataflow, but instead reduce the lenght to 55.066315446 
I can see Dataflow creates the column i BigQuery as datatype Numeric, however it should probably of datatype Float instead. 

I know this is not officielle supported yet (but in testing), but I could not see any bug issues for this.

### Beam Version

Newer than 2.46.0

### Relevant log output

_No response_

comment.diff_hunk:
@@ -159,6 +159,18 @@ public interface Options extends PipelineOptions {
     ValueProvider<Compression> getCompression();
 
     void setCompression(ValueProvider<Compression> value);
+
+    @TemplateParameter.Text(
+        order = 5,
+        optional = true,
+        regexes = {"^[A-Za-z_0-9.]*"},
+        description = "Output filename suffix",
+        helpText =
+            "Output filename suffix of the files to write. Defaults to .bzip2, .deflate or .gz depending on the compression algorithm.")
+    @Required
comment.body:
This confused me too and I am actually not sure what `@Required` does here or why it seems required by the code, but without it the resulting template did not know the `outputFilenameSuffix` parameter:

> ERROR: (gcloud.dataflow.jobs.run) INVALID_ARGUMENT: (451b3c759e4a9769): The workflow could not be created. Causes: (451b3c759e4a994c): Found unexpected parameters: ['outputFilenameSuffix' (perhaps you meant 'outputFailureFile')]

pull_request.title: BulkCompressor: Add optional parameter outputFilenameSuffix to overwrite default
pull_request.body:
For the bulk compress files template this adds a parameter `outputFilenameSuffix` to optionally set the output filename suffix to overwrite the default .bzip2, .deflate, .gz. with your own suffix or an empty string. Addresses #1131

Change is manually tested and confirmed to work with no parameter set (defaults to .bzip2, .deflate, .gz depending on the compression used so it's backwards compatible), parameter set to empty string and parameter set to custom ending like `.foo`.

Code was formatted with `mvn spotless:apply` and checked with `mvn spotless:check`. Autodocs were updated with `mvn clean prepare-package -DskipTests -PtemplatesSpec`.

Co-authored by @matheusfillipe (CLA was signed)

pull_request.title: Fix schema statement generation
pull_request.body:
This is a **big** PR.

The main goal is to make sure that only the required Cypher schema statements are generated.

Here are the following Neo4j schema "rules" that have guided the implementation of this PR:

- a node/rel key constraint (aka `key` or `keys` in the spec) is equivalent to the combination of non-null and unique constraints
- a node/rel key constraint is implicitly indexed (no index generation needed for the targeted properties)
- a uniqueness constraint  (aka `uniques` in the spec) is implicitly indexed (no index generation needed for the targeted properties)

This also streamlines the mapping to Cypher execution process:

- mapping (`JobSpecMapper` et al): remove all validation from there (see next point)
- validation (`InputValidator`): we want to validate as early as possible, but not too early (the mapper should map what it gets even if invalid).  Downstream components only deal with valid job specs.
- optimization (`InputRefactoring`): redundant mappings are ironed out, inactive targets are removed..  Downstream components only deal with valid, streamlined job specs.
- statement generation (`ModelUtils` / `CypherGenerator`): based on the aforementioned improvements, the generation logic is simplified. It also handles some specific cases better (like self-linking nodes that would normally lead to duplicate schema statements)

commits.message: Add failing test
Centralize all schema statements
Fix visibility

Iron out redundancies in target mappings

 - key implies unique/mandatory/indexed
 - unique implies indexed

Apply index_all_properties early

This simplifies the Cypher generation logic as indexed mappings
now refer to properties that are not keys, nor marked as uniques
and are explicitly indexed OR implicitly via index_all_properties.

Doing so makes the propagation of Config to CypherGenerator unneeded.
Remove redundant param
Remove inactive targets eagerly

Simplify Cypher schema statement generation

Now that InputRefactorer does the heavy lifting, all mappings
are guaranteed to not overlap with others.

This is the first commit that makes the e2e test go green.
Remove inactive targets, detect conflicting property mappings

Remove validation from MappingMapper

InputValidator now takes care of this

Deduplicate schema statements

This is useful when an edge target defines the same start and end
node (for self-linking purposes).
Add end-to-end tests with simple edge import
Fix job spec of single-pass import e2e tests

Do not mark mappings as unique/indexed, etc

`InputValidator` will deal with overlapping mappings downstream.
Reinstate mandatory (non-null) property mappings

Remove duplicate mapping of key/keys

key/keys could be defined in two places within the mappings
objects: at the top level and within the properties nested object.

This change makes it so that key/keys can only defined within the
properties objects, as this is more consistent with other schema-
related mappings (uniques, mandatory indexed).

This does NOT change how edge source/target nodes define their
key(s).
Detect conflicting property types
Merge mappings describing the same property (add type)
Fix test name case
Simplify test

issue.title: [Bug]: MongoDB to bigquery jobs with connection string in plain text on the console
issue.body:
### Related Template(s)

mongodb_to_bigquery_cdc

### What happened?

When creating mongodb jobs for bigquery, the template does not give the option to use the secret manager to query the connection string to connect to Mongodb. So, starting the job the way it is, the connection string is exposed in the console. This is a serious security issue.

### Beam Version

Newer than 2.46.0

### Relevant log output

_No response_
